ndinavian and other Germanic names, as well as names drawn from the Bible, the saints, and secular literature. Individual case studies include a comparison of naming in early medieval Scottish and Irish chronicles; an authoritative taxonomy of Gaelic names drawn from twelfth and thirteenth-century charters; a revolutionary new analysis of the emergence of surnames in Ireland, with implications for Scottish history; a complete linguistic discussion of the masculine Germanic names in the 1296 Ragman Roll; a detailed local case study of saints. names in Argyll which bears on place-names as well; and an examination of the adoption of Hebrew Old Testament names in central medieval Scotland. Dr MATTHEW HAMMOND is a Research Associate at Kings College London. Contributors: Rachel Butter, Thomas Owen Clancy, John Reuben Davies, Valeria DiClemente, Nicholas Evans, Matthew Hammond, Roibeard O Maolalaigh, David Sellar, Tom Turpie.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aBiblical Names.  aFrench romance literature.  aGaelic Names.  aIrish Names.  aScotland.  aScottish Names.  aScottish saints.  aearly medieval Chronicles.  anames.  anaming strategies.  aprosopography.  areligious names.1 aButter, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClancy, Thomas O, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClancy, Thomas Owen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClemente, Valeria Di, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, John Reuben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDi Clemente, Valeria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov